# üêû bug report

### Affected Package
The issue is caused by package @angular/language-service.

### Is this a regression?

I don't think so.

### Description

According to the [docs](https://angular.io/guide/structural-directives), the structural directive syntax

```
<ng-container *appTest="exp as value"></ng-container>
```

is desuggared into the following:

```
<ng-template [appTest]="exp" let-value="appTest">
    <ng-container></ng-container>
</ng-template>
```

If the structural directive has an `appTest` property on the context with which it creates the template which has a different type than what the `@Input() appTest` input takes (the type of `exp`), everything works functionally, but the language service seems to infer the type of `value` to be that of `exp` rather than the type defined by the context.

## üî¨ Minimal Reproduction

```
export class TestContext {
    public $implicit: number;
    public appTest: string;
}

@Directive({
    selector: "[appTest]",
})
export class AppTestDirective implements OnInit {
    exp: number;

    constructor (private viewContainer: ViewContainerRef, private templateRef: TemplateRef<any>) {}

    ngOnInit() {
        const context = new TestContext();
        context.$implicit = this.exp;
        context.appTest = `Test: ${this.exp}`;
        this.viewContainer.createEmbeddedView(this.templateRef, context);
    }

    @Input()
    public set appTest(exp: number) {
        this.exp = exp;
    }
}
```

Usage:

```
<p *appTest="5 as value">{{ value }}</p>
```

This *will* print `Test: 5`, but the inferred type for `value` is `number`.

It can be argued whether `x as y` should allow that `x` and `y` are of different types since this can be counter-intuitive (though in my use-case it probably isn't), but either way the behavior should be consistent.

